3D Coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 Protein Visualization with Biopython and nglview¶

Fan Wang¶

May 1 2021¶

To understand the structural biology of the SARS-CoV-2 virus, researchers must visualize complex protein structures. Exploring these structures is an important step in the process of drug design and docking studies that can be done in silico.


This notebook provides an example to manipulate DNA sequence, amino acid sequence and use visualization tools to present the three-dimensional (3D) structure of SARS-CoV-2 protein structures interactively.

Biopython Advantages¶

- Library of functions for biological computation
- Written in Python
- Distributed collaborative effort to develop Python libraries and applications
- Address the needs of current and future work in bioinformatics

Biopython Applications¶

1. Sequence Analysis (DNA/RNA/Protein)
2. Transcription & Translation studies
3. Accessing Bioinformatics Databases (NCBI, PDB)
4. 3D Structure Analysis

nglview Advantages¶

- An IPython/Jupyter widget
- View molecular structures and trajectories interactively

nglview Applications¶

1. Showing data from the file-system, RCSB PDB, simpletraj.
2. Showing data from objects of analysis libraries mdtraj, pytraj, mdanalysis, ParmEd, rdkit, ase, HTMD, biopython, cctbx, pyrosetta, schrodinger's Structure.

Table of contents:

  1. Import libraries & Understand FASTA file format
  2. Sequence manipulation using Biopython
  3. Transcription & Translation studies
  4. Perform Basic Local Alignment using NCBI-BLAST
  5. Reading PDB file
  6. Visualizing SARS-CoV-2 Protein Structure

3. Transcription & Translation Studies¶

DNA ---> RNA = **Transcription**
mRNA ---> Amino Acid (protein) = **Translation**
**3.1 Transcription:**

# Back transcribe

ATTAAAGGTT

Original length of the DNA sequence: 29903
Length of protein after translation: 9967

Please note that there are fewer sequences in the protein than the mRNA that is because 3 mRNAs are used to produce a single subunit of a protein, known as an amino acid, using the codon table shown below. The * is used to denote a stop codon, in these regions the protein has finished its full length. Many of these occur frequently and result in short lengths of protein, more likely than not these play a little biological role and will be excluded in further analyses.

Can protein sequences be reverse translated ?¶

Note: there is no function called `back_translate`.

This is also true for all the biological life too...¶

Note: we can't perform an exact `reverse translation` of course, since several amino acids are produced by the same codon.

)

**4.2 Query from [NCBI-BLAST Common URL API](https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi?PAGE_TYPE=BlastDocs&DOC_TYPE=CloudBlast) with Biopython's [`Bio.Blast.NCBIWWW`](https://biopython.org/docs/1.75/api/Bio.Blast.NCBIWWW.html) module**
In [27]:
%%time
result_handle = NCBIWWW.qblast("blastp", "pdb", read.seq)
blast_qresult = SearchIO.read(result_handle, "blast-xml")

Conclusion¶

  • Length 29903 base pairs
  • GC content 37.97%
  • Protein content has high L & the largest protein is of length 2701 Amino acid
  • Largest protein BLAST results corresponds to SARS-CoV-2 7D4F
  • Protein 7D4F has 4 chains
